sfi.description: circular section, folded edges
Bronze coin - oxidized. Rim on only one side. A recent scratch reveals gleaming metal underneath. Centre too built up with minerals and oxidization to see.
Probabile chiodo. Resta solo la Testa 15mm
Sez. quadr.; mancante della testa
Integro nella lunghezza; Sez. Quad. Testa 15mm Lunghezza Totale 6.5(4+2.5)cm
longitudinal, roughly circular cross-section; at both ends a globular mass ca. 0.4cm diameter; intervening material ca. 0.25cm diameter; heavily corroded/encrusted.

Fragment (possibly of cornice) seemingly comprising shallow concave cavetto ca 10 cm wide topped by a ca 2 cm wide fillet. One edge appears to have been roughly finished to a level surface as does "top" surface.
Rounded, flat clay bead with hole bored thoguh center. Orange. Not cicular, possibly rounded from square.
Superfici appiattite e sfaccettate; 1x1.2x2.3cm
N.2 frr.: length 3+3cm ca.; circular head  (2cm ca.)

Diameter is less than 0.05cm. 4 Fragments of copper/copper alloy strip or plate. Heavily corroded. Significant encrustations. Dimensions above are of largest fragment. Roughly rectangular with no regular sides. Other fragments are of similar material. Exact relationship between them difficult to establish. No piece has regular side/edge; all fragmented.

Copper/copper alloy wire, less then 0,1 cm dia. All surfaces corroded. Some encrustation at 2 junctions. 5 linked elements, hook loop linked to 4 looped elements. Hook: 1,9 cm long, dia of hook 0,9 cm look 0,35 cm dia, twisted through 90 degrees. 2nd element: 0,4 cm dia. Loop linked to 2nd look by 0.6 cm shaft; twisted through 90 degrees. 3rd element: as above; length of shaft ca. 7,5 cm. 4th element: as 2nd element. 5th element: 0.4 cm dia loop, 2.6 cm (remainder) of shaft. (By analogy with Sarachane (Istanbul) example, element 5 would have terminated in a hook and carried a further 2 hangers - type "C")
square section; track of head
Sez. Quad. Testa 15mm
Irregular shaped longitudinal object. Sides develop to a point at one end. In cross-section roughly flat rectangular (1,5 cm x 0,6 cm) one long side may have been knapped to form a sharp edge
Segment (about a third of upper part); upper element of omega/ rho monogram visible on one face, and rim; no feature visible on reverse; generally corroded/ encrusted.

Worked strip of bone. Incised design with three holes drilled through the top. Design is 2 lines straight across the top with interwoven 'swags' of 6 lines hung below them. Back has visible pored and is beginning to flake away. Other than cracks at either side, damage is minimal.
square ? sect.; circular head (2cm)

Length (ca 3cm) of copper/copper alloy wire 0.1 cm dia bent into loop form (dimensions above are of the loop shape). The 2 ends overlap each other to produce 0.2 thickness at that point. Corroded. Some encrustation.
Sez. Quad. Testa Mancante
obv; corrosion/ encrustation, rim, omega/rho monogram; rev; more heavily encrusted/ corroded; no details presently ascertainable but profile suggests may be revealed on cleaning.

two pieces which fit; white; substantially pitted/scarred; circular cross-section 0.6cm constant except at ends; at one end terminates in rounded element; at other, widening 0.6cm for 1.9cm; on outer surface 2, 0.2cm - 0.3cm, notches 0.6cm apart then bulbous element ca. 0.8cm diameter (and which projects ca. 0.2cm from inner aspect); finally terminating in an element 0.2cm wide which appears to be remnant of fully circular section.
ovoid section; blue glass
Roughly square block (one corner lost to either damge or rough finishing) out of which deep 10/ 11 cm depression has been formed (radius 13 cm).
triangular in plan on roughly square base. Apex squared off 2 cm by 2 cm. ca. 1,3 cm from top a 0,5 cm dia hole penetrates object. Fracture damage to part of apex, and to 3 sides at base.

3 pieces millstone ca 31 cm radius, based on two pieces showing curvature. 3rd piece reveals half of central hole ca 3.5 cm dia. Thickness at max (centre) 5.5cm; at min (edge) 2.5cm. Piece a.) curved, beveled edge longest (21.5cm) side, other edges fractured, width 11cm, thickness 5cm, reducing at one corner to 4cm. Piece b.) curved, beveled edge 19cm, 14.5cm wide, maximum thickness 4.5 cm. Piece c.) 18cm long, 15.5 cm wide, 5.5 cm thick (max) to 4 cm. At point of maximum thickness remains of 3.5cm dia. Hole

cxt.interpretation: This cut appears to be a late Roman or early Byzantine construction, perhaps a sunen basement for storage or perhaps water supply/drainage.
cxt.description: Large, very deep cut in the bedrock in the SE part of the room.  The cut is basically sqaure and measures slightly more than 2 1/2 meters deep, below the bedrock ridge on its NE side.  The cut narrows as it gets deeper, and also shows some signs of gouging (for beams?) along its vertical sides.
cxt.definition: Squared cut in bedrock in the E side of room 38

cxt.interpretation: Original wall of room 38, constructed at the same time as the rest of the complex (first phase); the material reused in it may have been taken from the ruins of monumental Greco-Roman structures in the vicinity
cxt.observations: NW face of this wall on plan is dubious -- probably not all material was cleared from above that face as of the end of 2005
cxt.description: Double course of roughly squared blocks and reused material (ashlar with anathyrosis and drafted margins; moulding; blocks with clamp holes); wall appears to be faced on both sides, but NW side not cleared during 2005 excavations
cxt.definition: Dry stone masonry wall of room 38 - NW wall

cxt.interpretation: Possibly filled in conjunction with creation of early Byzantine surface, but difficult to tell in absence of ceramic evidence
cxt.observations: Not yet clear if the wall foundation that runs into the middle of this pit was placed in a trench that cut the fill of the pit, or was simply placed on top of the fill itself -- needs further investigation
cxt.description: The fill of a circular pit/cut in bedrock; soft brownish soil, no ceramic, no bones; inclusions of clay, small stones. Diameter of the fill is approx. 50cm, depth 40cm; partly covered by walls of room 30 and 31a, so not fully excavated
cxt.definition: Fill of pit in NE part of room 37.
Stone positioned by the door between courtyard and room 32

cxt.interpretation: The trench for the electric cable.
cxt.observations: The cut was separated as a specific context only after finding the cable under the stones.
cxt.description: Trapezoid (in section) trench parallel to NE edge of the excavation area. Partially destroys wall, cuts down below the street level; runs whole length of excavation, about 80 cm wide at top, with sides narrowly as cut goes deeper; at least 75 cm deep (not fully excavated)
cxt.definition: Cut for the modern trench (for electric cable)

cxt.description: Il muro si conserva in alzato per tre filari ben definiti, mentre del quarto filare restano solo due blocchi informi. Si tratta di un muro a doppio paramento com insacco costituito da piccole pietre miste a terreno grigio, con radici e frammenti di laterizi. La tessitura sembra abbastanza regolare costituita da blocchi squadrati (vd. Schizzo scheda)

cxt.definition: Muro di cinta  con andamento N\W-S\E
Muro Perimetrale tra UF4 ed UF5 con andamento N\W - S\E

cxt.interpretation: or remains of some sort of modern construction?
cxt.description: The layer of white crumbly substance with a small pebble stones and sea shells in it. Thickness: 10-15 cm.
cxt.definition: Layer of white mortar at the top of cut 0936

cxt.description: Wall possibly contained courtyard 1 now partially destroyed by trench running E -> W. Large and small stone face. More of se face missing.
cxt.definition: Wall NW end of courtyard partially destroyed
Blocco di pietra lavorato in UF6A

cxt.interpretation: Wall constructed across the fill of a bedrock cut for some earlier building in this area -- no further information available; from the stratigraphic relationships, might belong to a late Early Byzantine building
cxt.description: Wall under wall 264: length 2.8m, width 30 cm in S part and 45cm in N part; only one course of masonry preserved, with mid-sized unworked but regular stones (35-45cm in longest dimension); runs roughly NW-SE, but on a slightly different axis from the wall above (W of NW); no foundation trench noted, single course of masonry rests directly on soil fill
see context sheet from 2004 for description
Strato di terreno sciolto di colore grigio scuro con radici. I pochi frr di ceramica, piccole pietre e ossi di animali probabilmente provengono dalla us 86.

Strato di crollo composto da pietre di differenti dimensioni e terra di colore bruno. Alcune pietre presentano segni di sbozzatura. Notevole presenza di materiali moderni (vetro e lamine metalliche) e frr. di ceramica di varii periodi. Lo strato di crollo e presente anche nel contiguo ambiente 25 sopra l'USCHPA51

cxt.interpretation: Earlier bedrock cut of uncertain purpose?
cxt.description: Rectangle-like cut in the south corner of room 30, 1.2 x 2m, ca. 50-60cm deep, fairly straight sides
cxt.definition: Cut of large hole/disturbance in the southeast end of room 30

cxt.interpretation: Metal working associated feature, possibly hearth
cxt.observations: Some type of metal working associated feature? Excavated to approximately 15 cm in depth; had to return to finish excavating because it wasn’t all removed on the first go around. After cleaning the profile it appears that 524 is connected/associated with context 587.
cxt.description: Dimensions are 52 cm N-S, 40 cm E-W, and 25 cm in depth; fine ashy soil with many pieces of slag both metal and vitreous. The context extends into the profile of the unexcavated [section of the] courtyard. Filled an irregular cut in 2 surfaces under the last courtyard surface (509).
cxt.definition: Black ashy soil in west section of courtyard
Muro perimetr. tra  Vano 1 e Vano 2 con andamento S\W-N\E

cxt.interpretation: Sparse ceramic material from this hearth suggests a date in the 11th c. (GWW II, glazed polychrome WW)
cxt.description: 24 x 20 cm "staple" shaped hearth feature on floor of 672. Thin 2 cm walls. Grey-ash smooth and compact overlying a dark chocolate brown, patch of burnt (?) earth or a roughly square shape.

Struttura di forma squadrata rozzamente costruita con blocchi irregolari. Misure interne (2,24x1,10 m; profond. 50 cm ca). Fondo piatto. Nella costruzione tra i blocchi si legge un legante molto rozzo, una specie di cemento in cui sono presenti vistosi frr. di laterizi e pietra calcarea. Simile a Vasca 1 e Vasca 2.

cxt.interpretation: Possible paved path running adjacent to the staircase.
cxt.observations: Excavation of context was begun only momentarily, then saved in order to float (or wait until next season).
cxt.description: Compact grayish brown (10YR 5/2), very gravely consistentcy with inclusions of 10YR 6/3 and 10YR 8/1. The layer runs in the west wing of room 31 adjacent to the staircase.
cxt.definition: Compacted light gravel surface adjacent to staircase

cxt.interpretation: Still interpreted as "packing" for preparation for floor/living surface (SR435), however, the fill of the gaps in bedrock is an earlier layer assigned context number SR468.
cxt.observations: Originally identified as packing for cracks/gaps in bedrock - this fill was later determined to be SR468 after seeing the relationship shown in photo 263.  The bags for this layer will include material that should now be with 468 (not identified until after some had been excavated).
cxt.description: Dark grayish brown, clayey layer containing bone, ceramic, and some metal.  Soil is "gummy"/clayey and was primarily located in southern half of room.

cxt.observations: Large late wall in courtyard removed in 2002.
cxt.description: Tratto di muro a secco conservato solo nel primo filare, costituito da blocchi appena sbozzati. Nel sacco sono visibili terra, piccole pietre, frr. di laterizi e ceramica
